article.headline: Princeton 44, Lehigh 43
article.story: PRINCETON, N.J. (AP) -- It's safe to say that Princeton's starting freshmen guards will have fond memories of their collegiate home debut. Marcus Schroeder hit a foul shot with no time left to give Princeton a 44-43 victory over Lehigh on Wednesday night. And Lincoln Gunn, his partner in the backcourt, helped make the win possible by scoring six of his career-high 12 points in the final five minutes. The two also were teammates at California's De La Salle High School last year. "It was nice," Schroeder said. "I didn't feel like I played great tonight, but Lincoln stepped up on the second half and made some huge three's for us. I kind of redeemed myself with the free throw at the end." In beating Lehigh (4-7) for the 23rd consecutive time, Princeton (6-2) is off to its best start since the 1997-98 team opened 7-1 en route to a one-loss regular-season. Lehigh's Kyle Neptune led all scorers with 15 points, while Jason Mgebroff finished with 12 points and 11 rebounds. Gunn led the Tigers with a career-high 12 points. Trailing 43-41, Lehigh had tied the game with 21.8 seconds left when Marquis Hall penetrated and dished to Mgebroff for a layup. However, Princeton played on instead of calling a timeout. Edwin Buffmire then missed a jumper in the closing seconds, but Schroeder grabbed the long rebound on the right baseline and was fouled while throwing up a desperation shot as the buzzer sounded. He then made the first foul shot to win the game. "I was trying to make the shot when I shot it, but when I got that rebound I was just trying to draw a foul," Schroeder said. "I was a little surprised to get the call, but to be honest, I got fouled pretty hard on that play." Lehigh coach Billy Taylor refused to criticize referee Gary Agger for his call. "A call was made, there's nothing I can do about it," Taylor said. "They said they blew the whistle and the horn sounded right after that. We thought we were in position to win the game or go into overtime (but), unfortunately, it didn't work out down the stretch." Princeton coach Joe Scott was sympathetic toward Taylor and his team. "Everybody knows we were just lucky," said Scott, who was forced to start three freshmen with forward Justin Conway out with an abdomen injury. "When you get a call like that, we're just lucky. We have to play better so a call like that doesn't go against us. That's just pure luck there.
